StringEscapeUtils.escapeJavaScript() method did not escape '/' into '\/', it will make IE render page uncorrectly
If Javascripts including'/', IE will parse the scripts uncorrectly, actually '/' should be escaped to '\/'. For example, document.getElementById("test").value = '<script>alert(\'aaa\');</script>';this expression will make IE render page uncorrect, it should be document.getElementById("test").value = '<script>alert(\'aaa\');<\/script>'; Btw, Spring's JavascriptEscape behavor is correct. Try  to run below codes, you will find the difference:   String s = "<script>alert('aaa');</script>";   String str = org.springframework.web.util.JavaScriptUtils.javaScriptEscape(s);   System.out.println("Spring JS Escape : "+str);   str = org.apache.commons.lang.StringEscapeUtils.escapeJavaScript(s);   System.out.println("Apache Common Lang JS Escape : "+ str);